amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS), Parkinson’s disease (PD), multiple sclerosis (MS), or Huntington’s disease (HD).[<xref rid="R1" ref-type="bibr">1</xref>] The commentary is thought-provoking, but several points should be discussed.</p><p>The first point is that there are several arguments against the hypothesis that prolonged COVID-19 leads to neurodegenerative diseases. First, prolonged COVID-19 is rarely associated with structural or functional abnormalities in the nervous system.[<xref rid="R2" ref-type="bibr">2</xref><xref rid="R3" ref-type="bibr">3</xref>] Cerebral imaging is usually normal after SARS-CoV-2 infection unless the acute infection was complicated by encephalitis, meningitis, stroke, sinus vein thrombosis, vasoconstriction syndrome, or hemorrhage.[<xref rid="R4" ref-type="bibr">4</xref>] Therefore, it could be useful to distinguish between long-COVID-19 patients in whom there was cerebral involvement clinically, morphologically, or functionally and those in whom this was not the case. Patients with structural cerebral lesions as a result of the infection are more likely to have long-term complications than patients without these lesions.[<xref rid="R5" ref-type="bibr">5</xref>] Second, SARS-CoV-2 has rarely been detected in the cerebrospinal fluid of patients with cerebral involvement during acute infection. Third, although virus particles were found in all brain regions in COVID-19 patients at autopsy, these regions show little inflammation or virus cytopathology.[<xref rid="R6" ref-type="bibr">6</xref>] Fourth, there are no studies that clearly demonstrate that the prevalence of SDAT, ALS, MS, HD, or PD has actually increased since the end of the pandemic.</p><p>The second point is that long-COVID is explained by mechanisms, for which there is limited evidence. Long-COVID-19 has been explained by viral persistence, immunothrombosis, fusion of neurons with glial cells, neuroinflammation, decreased neurogenesis, hypocorticism due to hypothalamic–pituitary axis dysfunction, and vagal dysfunction due to dysbiosis.[<xref rid="R1" ref-type="bibr">1</xref>] Currently, there is not much evidence that long-COVID-19 is due to venous sinus thrombosis (VST), pituitary dysfunction, or vagal dysfunction.[<xref rid="R7" ref-type="bibr">7</xref>] VST has rarely been reported in the acute phase of SARS-CoV-2 infection and is limited to this phase of the disease.[<xref rid="R8" ref-type="bibr">8</xref>] Hypometabolism in certain brain regions (e.g., olfactory bulbs) can hardly explain the general symptoms of long COVID-19 (impaired memory, concentration, cognition, executive functions, fatigue, and exercise intolerance). There is also little evidence that the skeletal muscles are generally affected in long-COVID-19 and are therefore responsible for fatigue as one of the main symptoms. Only in patients who have acquired myositis during the acute phase of SARS-CoV-2 infection can skeletal muscle changes be detected.[<xref rid="R9" ref-type="bibr">9</xref>]</p><p>Third, HD or MS are not generally considered neurodegenerative diseases.[<xref rid="R1" ref-type="bibr">1</xref>] HD is generally considered a genetic disorder caused by a cytosin, adenine, guanine (CAG) repeat expansion &gt; 35 in the HTT gene.[<xref rid="R10" ref-type="bibr">10</xref>] MS is an immunological disorder that is most likely triggered by previous viral infections.[<xref rid="R11" ref-type="bibr">11</xref>] Whether SARS-CoV-2 is actually involved in the development of prion diseases is controversial. In single cases, prion disease after COVID-19 has been reported, but the causal link remained unproven.[<xref rid="R12" ref-type="bibr">12</xref>] There is currently no increase in the prevalence of prion diseases worldwide.</p><p>The fourth point is that the proposed treatment of long-COVID-19 with fluoxetine or sertraline is usually of limited benefit. Since the underlying pathophysiology of long-COVID-19 is multifactorial, it is unlikely that a single SSRI can influence all pathophysiological mechanisms, leading to long-COVID-19.</p><p>To summarize, some of the statements in the index study are speculative and not supported by evidence. There is currently no proven case of a patient with long COVID-19 who has developed SDAT, ALS, or prion disease. Individual studies reporting abnormalities in patients with long COVID-19 provide limited evidence to support the hypothesis put forward in the index study. Longitudinal studies and biomarker research are desirable to add depth and highlight the importance of an evidence-based approach.</p><sec disp-level="2"><title>Author contributions</title><p>JF was responsible for the design and conception, discussed available data with coauthors, wrote the first draft, and gave final approval.</p></sec><sec disp-level="2"><title>Ethical policy and institutional review board statement</title><p>Not applicable.</p></sec><sec sec-type="data-availability" disp-level="2"><title>Data availability statement</title><p>The datasets generated during and/or analyzed during the current study are available from the corresponding author on reasonable request.</p></sec><sec sec-type="COI-statement" disp-level="2"><title>Conflicts of interest</title><p>There are no conflicts of interest.</p></sec></body><back><ref-list><ref id="R1"><label>1</label><element-citation publication-type="journal" publication-format="print"><person-group person-group-type="author">
